The Australian Fisheries Management Authority (AFMA) is the Australian Government statutory authority responsible for the management and sustainable use of fisheries resources and for combating illegal fishing activities in the Australian Fishing Zone that covers 8,148,250 square kilometres, the third largest in the world, and in Australia's Exclusive Economic Zone, which extends from 12 nautical miles to 200 nautical miles (370 km) from the coastline of Australia and its external territories, except where a maritime delimitation agreement exists with another state. To the 12 nautical miles boundary is Australiaâ€™s territorial waters. (See also Seas and Submerged Lands Act 1973.) The Australian Fishing Zone covers Australian waters, generally from 3 to 200 nautical miles (370 km) from the Australian coast.
AFMA is an agency of the Australian Department of Agriculture and Water Resources.
